o arise from the Breton personal name <i>Houuel</i>, <i>Huwel</i>, <i>Huwal</i>, <i>Howael</i>, cognate with the Welsh name. Bretons were especially numerous in the eastern counties of England. See   Powell  .","English: perhaps from a Middle English personal name <i>Huwel</i> (spelled <i>Howel</i>), a shortening of <i>Huwelot</i> or <i>Huelin</i> (see   Hewlett   and   Huling  ), both pet forms of Middle English <i>Huw</i> (see   Hugh  ).","English: habitational name from Howell (Lincolnshire), from an uncertain initial element + Old English <i>wella</i> ‘well, spring, stream’."],"variants":[{"name":"Howle","meanings":["English and Welsh:","variant of   Howell  .","variant of   Hole  ."]},{"name":"Howells","meanings":["English and Welsh (Glamorgan): variant of   Howell  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent English <i>-s</i>.","English: perhaps occasionally a nickname for someone who was fearless, from Middle English <i>houe</i>, <i>houwe</i> ‘anxiety, fear’ (Old English <i>hogu</i> or <i>hoga</i>) + <i>les</i> ‘less’. If this has survived as a modern surname, its pronunciation has been influenced by that of the name in 1 above.","English: variant of   Holes  ."]},{"name":"Powell","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap Hywel</i> ‘son of <i>Hywel</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘eminent’ (see   Howell  ).","Irish: mainly of Welsh origin as in 1 above, but sometimes a surname adopted as equivalent of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Phóil</b> ‘son of the servant of Saint Paul’ (see   Guilfoyle  ).","English: variant of   Paul   or   Poole  ."]}]},{"name":"Mabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a nickname from the Old French vocabulary word <i>amabel</i>, <i>amable</i> ‘lovely’ (akin to modern English <i>amiable</i> ‘friendly, good-humoured’). The initial vowel began to be lost as early as the 12th century (the same woman is referred to as both <i>Mabilia</i> and <i>Amabilia</i> in a document of  1185 ), but a short vowel in the resulting first syllable was standard, giving a rhyme with <i>babble</i>, until the 19th century, when people began to pronounce the name to rhyme with <i>table</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Verch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Orlo.","German: variant of   Ferch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferch","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mabel Verch Howell was born in 1362, in Merionethshire, Wales, her father, Hywel ap Iorwerth Fychan ap Iorwerth ap Gwarin ap Caradog ap Ynyr Fychan, was 93 and her mother, Jane ferch Hywel Or Howell x, was 93. She had at least 1 daughter with Sir Thomas Ireland. She died in 1434, in her hometown, at the age of 72."},"et":{"1362–1434":"1362–1434","1125–Female":"1125–Surnud","1244–Male":"1244–Surnud","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","–1338":"–1338","1360–1436":"1360–1436","1373–Male":"1373–Surnud","1402–1510":"1402–1510","1392–1430":"1392–1430","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","about 1392":"umbes 1392","1362":"1362","1373":"1373","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1338":"1338","1436":"1436","14 February 1402":"14. veebruar 1402","1402":"1402","1434":"1434","1510":"1510","1125":"1125","1244":"1244","1430":"1430","about 1430":"umbes 1430","Oswestry, Shropshire, England":"Oswestry, Shropshire, England","Merionethshire, Wales":"Merionethshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1362–1434":"1362–1434","1125–Female":"1125–Kuollut","1244–Male":"1244–Kuollut","1260–Male":"1260–Kuollut","–1338":"–1338","1360–1436":"1360–1436","1373–Male":"1373–Kuollut","1402–1510":"1402–1510","1392–1430":"1392–1430","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1270–Female":"1